[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In this video, [music] I\'ll show you why Mago is now the best way to create AI VFX. I\'ll teach you how to easily create some insane [music] AI VFX shots along with my pro tips. Okay, let\'s get into it. I\'ve been using Mago for a while now'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I believe it is an AI VFX powerhouse. With the additions like Nano Banana Pro for image editing and the addition of video models like Cling, it is insanely good for AI VFX. And I\'ve'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'got some incredible examples to show you. Make sure to check them all out as they all use different techniques and I\'ll be throwing in loads of tips. I\'ll quickly show you how I created that arm'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cannon shot from the intro. So, I\'ve got this short clip here and I want to turn my arm into a kind of weaponized arm cannon. So, within Mago, you can see I\'ve got all my projects here on the left hand side. So, I\'ve created a new project here in Mago. All you have to do'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is drag in the video that you want to edit and then it will appear with this window where you can trim the video if you want to. Now the video is loaded. We can see it on the right hand side here. So you can play back if you want to. And the blue slider up here, this is the'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'range of frames that you\'re going to export in the final video. This is really handy if you just want to export a few frames to see how the video is going to look. And then you can choose to do the whole video after. We can see the big video preview in the middle. And'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the left here, this is where we\'re going to dial in all the settings. And Mago give you a ton of options to choose from. What I like about it is that you get to really fine-tune the settings to how you want that specific video to look. And here we have some really'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'helpful built-in presets. So, as you can see, they\'ve got different presets for just replacing a character in a scene, a character and background, do basic restyle. They\'ve even got a preset for fastmoving videos, which is extremely'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'helpful, and presets for multiple characters, editing certain parts of the video, ones that work best for close-up shots, and they\'ve even got a dreamlike and abstract effects preset. Personally, I like to manually tweak the settings as'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I really like to iterate on videos and see what settings do what to the video as you can get some pretty wild results just by adjusting the settings slightly. So, in the Mago engine, we have the older models down at the bottom. I'

[02:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'usually use first frame version 3.3 or 3.4. We also have a creative upscaler, which is really handy. And then we have the animate v1 and v1 background. These are perfect for animating different'

[02:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'characters and replacing your characters and background together. I\'ll show you some examples using this model shortly. For this video, I\'ll use first frame version 3.4. And over on control net, we can see all of the different control net'

[02:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'types. For this one, I\'ll stick to pose, but I\'ll also show you the versions with the other control nets as well, just so you can see how different they look. I usually keep most of the settings the same, so I\'ll keep face mesh on. And then if we go to advanced, most of these'

[02:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I just keep as their standard settings, but I would urge you to actually have a play around with these settings to try get different results. Now I\'m going to edit the frame to add that cannon onto my arm. So you can either go to stylize frame or modify frame up here. So as you'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can see here, this is the very first frame of the video, which is the one that I want to edit. Now, you don\'t necessarily have to edit the first frame. Now, you might be wondering, what if my character\'s not at the start of my video? Do I have to start at the first'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame? You can actually choose the frame where your character is in the shot and then edit that and Mago will look at that and change it accordingly. I\'ll show you an example of that shortly. Then we have a bunch of image editors to choose from. So we have Cream, Nano'

[03:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Banana Pro, Quen Image Edit, Mago, Context, and the original Nano Banana, but I\'m going to go for Nano Banana Pro because it is just an incredible image editor. And you can actually upload a'

[03:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reference image if you want it to look at that. But for this one, I\'m just going to use a text prompt. So, I\'ve used this prompt here of turn just his arm into an arm cannon weapon like in Metroid, keep exactly the same pose and composition. So, hopefully it should'

[03:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keep everything else in the image the same and just change my arm. So, I\'ve generated a few different images and as you can see some of them here and the results look awesome. A few of these have the effect over my shoulder which I'

[03:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'didn\'t want. I really like this one. As you can see, it goes under my t-shirt so it looks like it\'s part of my body. And in this image here, I actually completely changed my character. And soon I\'ll show you how that looks as well. But for this VFX, I just really'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wanted to focus on changing one part of the video, but keeping everything else the same. Then all you have to do is click on use this. And as you can see, it\'s already added that frame over here. Now, what\'s really cool, if you look'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'below, we have the prompt for the video. So what Mago will do, it will look at the video and image, and it will generate a description. So as you can see, it\'s done a pretty good job at describing that image. It\'s included the sci-fi bionic arm, metal textures, and'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s got the right information about what I look like and the environment I\'m in. Then all you have to do is make sure you\'ve selected the right amount of frames that you want to export. You can do generate or you can do a test render where Mago just use a few frames for a'

[04:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower cost. I\'ve already rendered out a video and here\'s what it looks like. I\'m really happy with that. And up here you can do side by side view. So if you want to see the new render against the original video, you can do that. And if we play it back, you can see it follows'

[04:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it pretty well. You might notice that my face looks slightly different in the new render. And that\'s where I usually take my shots and crop into the original footage. This isn\'t necessary on all shots, but for this kind of shot where'

[05:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s using myself, I want to make sure that it does look like me. So, for that, I usually take this video, place it on top of the original footage, and then use an opacity mask to then select the area that I want to keep from the'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original video. And it blends in really well. So this is how all the different control nets look. And as you can see, they can drastically change the output of the video. For that example, I did just use my arm, but you can actually'

[05:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use props as well. So in the intro shot, I actually used this cardboard tube that I had around my arm. And it does look a bit silly, but this can really help to keep the consistency of this shape. For this test, I have some flames coming out'

[05:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the weapon. And I thought if I move the weapon closer to the camera, would you be able to see inside of it and the flames coming out? So, I\'ve got the video here where I start more of a profile view and then I swing my arm around in front of the camera. I'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generated a few different looks using Nano Banana. And I really liked this image of this weapon. So, I\'ve got the steam coming out of it. You can see some flames out the front. For this video, I actually used the soft edge control net. So, it\'s definitely worth trying out'

[06:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different models. If we watch it back, you can actually see the animated flame within the gun, which I think is a really cool touch. And I really like how when I move the gun to the front of the camera, the front of the gun is out of focus, which is exactly how I wanted it.'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And when merged with my original footage, it just looks really good. Now, on the right here, you\'ve probably seen that I\'ve done loads of different renders. This is another thing I really like about Maggo is they have this'

[06:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vertical timeline. So, within each project, you can see every render you\'ve done. You can quickly look between each of them. It just makes it so easy to follow everything that you\'ve done within that project. If you really like one of the renders that you\'ve done and'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want to redo them, you just click on these arrows here and it will paste all of the settings back into the settings area from that render. You can download your video here and if you click on the three buttons here, I really like the iterate function. What iterate will do,'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it will take that render that you\'ve created and then you can do further adjustments to it. I\'ll show you more of this later on as I think it\'s a really good approach to editing your videos. I find it\'s good to do one edit at a time using the iterate feature as sometimes'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if you try to do too many things in one shot, it will kind of break down and won\'t look that good. This effect was inspired by the Predator Badlands film as one of the characters is an android with half her body missing and I thought, could I try that effect on'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'myself? So, I filmed a bunch of different clips and I\'ve had some pretty interesting results. Some of them did not work, but the ones that did worked better when I actually had shorts on. then the video model used my short line as a good place for the effect to end.'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Otherwise, if I wore trousers, the effect wouldn\'t work as well. Anyway, here\'s a few clips of where I\'ve removed parts of my body. Maggo works great if you want to turn'

[08:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yourself into different characters. I\'ve got a few awesome examples. So, this first one of me is a kind of slightly out of focus shot of me pretending to hold a candle. Then I used Nano Banana and said, "Turn myself into a wizard'

[08:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'holding a candle in an old tavern in claymation style." And the image looks awesome. For this one, I used the Animate version one background model and it looks great. The background is even animated in a really nice subtle way.'

[08:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The candle light is also casting a light and shadow, which is a really nice touch. If you just want to change your character but not the background, then just use the Animate V1 model like I\'ve done in these videos here. So, here I'

[08:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'changed my head into an orc head and it has perfect lip syncing. And this one is awesome. So, I use Nano Banana Pro to turn my face into a Predator face. I think this is incredible. If you look at all the features around the mouth, it\'s'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all moving really organically and natural. I thought this shot worked really well. These close-up face videos work really well with the Animate V1 model. Now, let\'s have a look at using Cling in Mago to create AI VFX. This Clinger O1 model is incredible for AI'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'VFX as you can input any video and write into the prompt what you want to change. So, let\'s have a look at some of my examples. So, for this first one, I filmed myself in my garden with a moving camera motion, and I wanted to turn'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'myself into a different character. And for this shot, I wanted to do different iterations. So, first I want to change my character, and then I\'ll change the background. I wanted to turn myself into a Predator for this one. So, I used Nano'

[09:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Banana Pro to change the first frame of this video. I did use a reference image from the Predator Badlands film as I wanted it to look like this specific Predator. And the result looks incredible. I still can\'t believe just how good Nano Banana Pro is at creating'

[09:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these kind of shots. Then in Mago, just make sure you\'ve selected Clinger 01. And below the prompt, you can add in two images and two element images. So for the images, this is really good if you'

[10:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have an image of a certain scenery or style you want the video to be in. And for elements, this works well if you have a specific character in mind and you have to give it two different angles. The best way to get multiple camera angles of a character is using'

[10:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Nano Banana Pro and prompt it with create different angles of this character. So this is an example of the Predator character that I used with Nano Banana Pro to change the camera angle. So it\'s created a new angle of the character. So if you want the best'

[10:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'results for including a character, animal, or object in a video, then definitely use the elements feature. But for this one, I\'m just using the image tab with that image of me as a predator. So I\'ve put into the prompt change the'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'person into the predator in image one. As you can see here, we\'ve got the element one, image one, and image two buttons here. And if you click on them, it will add that into the prompt. So, this just tells Mago to look at that'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image as reference. And this is the video it created. I am blown away by this, to be honest. It looks so good. It\'s even got my mouth movements on the character. And the background is moving perfectly like the original video. It\'s'

[11:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'super impressive. This is going to be extremely powerful if you want to replace a character. Now I want to iterate on this video to change the background. So to do that just click on the three dots there and then click iterate. So now we can edit that video.'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I wanted to change the background to a forest. So I generated this image of a forest in Nano Banana Pro and I\'ve uploaded it into the image tab here. Then I just prompted in Mago change the background to this forest and then the'

[11:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image one and then the reference to image one there and match the lighting. And this is what the video looks like. I\'m really happy with this even though at the end you can see my shed comes into it, but that doesn\'t always happen.'

[11:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'As you can see in this one here, it does it all the way round. I\'m really impressed with this as it\'s matched the actual camera motion to the original video and managed to fill out the rest of the forest behind the character from me in my background to this. It\'s just'

[11:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pretty mind-blowing that we can do this now. And then I wanted to see if I could get the background to be more animated. So I actually created this background of a forest on fire with a creature in the background when I generated that video.'

[12:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is the result it created. This is really cool as now we have the character animation and the background is animated as well in a really cool way. Then I wanted to test the upscaler in Mago. Now to upscale one of your renders just make'

[12:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sure to click on iterate then come over to the Mago engine and select the creative upscaler. Another cool thing you could do in this'

[12:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt here, I actually added two different background images. And in the finished video, it\'s actually blended both of them together, which I thought was really creative. And if you want, you can just keep iterating on your videos to keep adding different effects.'

[12:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here\'s another version where I used the classic Predator, which I think looks really cool. And then I even changed the background to this one. I love this one as it feels like it\'s telling a story. you feel like the Predator has crashed his ship on this'

[13:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planet. And we even have some animated ships in the sky. Definitely play around with this technique. It\'s really fun to play around with. And here\'s a few other videos where I\'ve done different iterations to get to the final product. Now, I want to show you this really cool'

[13:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'technique where you can use markers to put specific effects. So, for this one, I just drew an X on my arm and then did a quick recording. And I prompted it with, "There is a hole revealing bone where the X is." And it\'s kind of gross,'

[13:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but I was really impressed with the video. It definitely feels like you can see through my skin to the muscle. It\'s extremely gross, but I was really impressed with this effect. I\'ve done another similar one here for a kind of gunshot wound. I could see this effect'

[13:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'being used for kind of lowbudget things if you wanted to add wounds to people. I think it works really well and is tracked perfectly. And in this one, I used an image reference of a scorpion. And I said, "There is a scorpion walking where the X is." It looks really good.'

[13:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It actually looks like there\'s a little scorpion on my arm. And I did a similar thing here where I put some blue tape on the floor to resemble an X. And I just filmed around it. And this one I gave it two reference images of a banana and an'

[14:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'eagle. And then I said there are these two images on the ground where the blue X is. And it looks great. The two objects are there perfectly standing on the X. So you can use these tracking markers to put objects in the perfect'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'place in your scene. Otherwise, without the tracking marker, the object might be in a random place where you don\'t want it. You don\'t have to just use people in your videos. Like in this example here, I filmed myself picking up a pen, and I'

[14:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wanted the hand to look like a predator hand. So, I changed my hand in nano banana. And this is the video in Mago using the Animator V1 model. I was really happy with how it turned out. And I think overall, Mago did an awesome job'

[14:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at changing my hand into a Predator style hand. This is a really good example if you want to create different kind of shots. and it helps you to create different camera angles and tell different story beats. You can do so many things using the Cling video edit'

[14:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model. Like in this video here, I just filmed a short clip of myself reacting to something behind me and then in Mago selecting the Clink engine, I just prompted it with there is an explosion in the back left area. Keep everything'

[15:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'else unchanged. And it creates a really cool explosion and it does kind of look like I\'m reacting to it. You can also change the backgrounds, like I\'ve put myself in a stadium. And in this one, I'

[15:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even added a fire breathing dragon onto the fence, which I was really impressed with. And then I thought, could I create an effect that\'s around me? So, I actually ended up flooding my garden. I did make sure to mask out my face to get'

[15:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the original performance. And I am blown away with the finished result. To me, it looks really realistic, and this is a really good way of creating these kind of VFX shots. It\'s also great at changing elements, like if you want to'

[15:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'add snow into your shot, if you want it to be raining, you can really go wild and change the look of your scene. Now, this effect really surprised me. I filmed myself pretending to drag something quite heavy. So, as you can'

[15:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see, I\'m holding on to nothing. Then, I edited the image in Nano Banana Pro to make it look like I\'m dragging a heavy boulder with a rope. Then I used that video and that image using the cling model and prompted it with he is'

[16:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dragging the boulder with a rope like in this image and I was incredibly impressed with the video it created. So as you can see I\'m pulling that rope and the boulder is moving as well. Now I know the physics are kind of off and the'

[16:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'angle is a bit weird but I\'m still really impressed that this worked. I hope this can unlock some kind of ideas that you\'ve got and really push the boundaries with what\'s possible on this model. A tip here, if you\'re only'

[16:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'changing a small part of the video, like in this video here where I\'m just changing the effect on my arm, then I usually create a new video of my arm cropped in, then use Nano Banana to create a new effect on my arm, render out that video, and then take that video'

[16:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and crop it back onto the original footage. I find this method really good for getting more detailed VFX for smaller areas of the video. And I did the same for this video here, where I just wanted to do an effect on my arm. I wanted to try an impainting V effect'

[16:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot and I created something that looks pretty gross. So, here\'s a warning for the next one. I wanted to see if I could create like a ripped skin effect revealing something underneath. So, for this one, this is the original video and'

[17:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then I created a cropped video just of my arm as that\'s the only place where I want the effect to be. Then I used Nano Banana Pro to create this image with the effect that I want. I know it\'s very gross, so I\'m really sorry for how it'

[17:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looks. I ran it through twice with Mago using the soft edge model and the pose model and I think the results look incredibly realistic. It\'s done a great job at moving all the tendons as I kind of twist my arm and even moves the flaps'

[17:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of skin hanging off as well in a realistic way. So yeah, this is really gross, but I\'m very impressed with it. Then I tried a different version with a more kind of mechanical robot inside to the arm. And again, it knocked it out of'

[17:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the park. And here\'s an example where I changed the frame from the middle of the video and not from the start. As you can see, the person enters in the middle of the video. So, this shows you can edit'

[18:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'characters even if they\'re not in the start of the video. The great thing is Maggo is open to everyone now. I\'ve left a link to it in the description below for you to sign up. You can get 60% off your first month of a pro plan with the'

[18:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code atomic pro, which is only available for the first 500 people. So, make sure to get in quick. Make sure to click the link in the description to sign up to Mago. All right, I [snorts] hope you\'ve learned something new in this video and'

[18:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I hope I\'ve inspired you to go and create some incredible AI VFX. Definitely give Mago a go. They\'ve added so many incredible tools for you to create whatever AI VFX that you want to now, and it\'s [clears throat] just'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'incredibly fun to use. So, if you do want to see more videos like this, make sure to give it a like and subscribe to my channel. Feel free to comment down below if there\'s an AIV effect shot that you want me to cover in a future video and I\'ll make sure to include it in the'

[18:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next one. Well, I\'m going to do more experimenting now. My name is Jack and I will see you in the next one.'
